<subSubSection id="C3616572FFB9E453A8B553D84020FD81" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC436F9FFB9E453A8B553D84020FD81" blockId="25.[151,1437,151,608]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="B90FEAEBFFB9E453A8B553D8404CFE31" bold="true" box="[199,335,439,464]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Comments.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion id="49BFF81BFFB9E453A92553D74068FE31" box="[343,363,440,464]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">A</collectingRegion>
larva was found making a similar mine in a leaf of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D7AFFB9E453ABCE53D84400FE31" authority="Thunb." authorityName="Thunb." box="[956,1283,439,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeagnaceae" genus="Elaeagnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umbellata">
<emphasis id="B90FEAEBFFB9E453ABCE53D845A9FE31" box="[956,1194,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Elaeagnus umbellata</emphasis>
Thunb.
</taxonomicName>
a few meters from the 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D7AFFB9E453A97653B34080FE14" box="[260,387,476,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeagnaceae" genus="Shepherdia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEAEBFFB9E453A97653B34080FE14" box="[260,387,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Shepherdia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plants, but we were unable to rear it. This is the only leaf mine we have ever seen on 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D7AFFB9E453ADF653B24004FDF9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeagnaceae" genus="Elaeagnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umbellata">
<emphasis id="B90FEAEBFFB9E453ADF653B24004FDF9" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. umbellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a common invasive shrub in New 
<collectingCountry id="F36C7669FFB9E453AAB253904223FDF9" box="[704,800,511,536]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">England</collectingCountry>
, and it was almost certainly a larva of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D7AFFB9E453AD7B506F401CFDDC" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Amauromyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shepherdiae">
<emphasis id="B90FEAEBFFB9E453AD7B506F401CFDDC" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Amauromyza shepherdiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, possibly occurring on this plant only because of its proximity to the rare native shrub that is this fly’s normal host.
</paragraph>
